# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: strassen-matrix
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Because matrix multiplication is such a central operation in many numerical algorithms, much work has been invested in making **matrix multiplication algorithms** efficient.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Applications of matrix multiplication in computational problems are found in many fields including scientific computing and pattern recognition and in seemingly unrelated problems such as counting the paths through a graph.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Many different algorithms have been designed for multiplying matrices on different types of hardware, including parallel and distributed systems, where the computational work is spread over multiple processors (perhaps over a network).
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Directly applying the mathematical definition of matrix multiplication gives an algorithm that takes time on the order of *n*3 field operations to multiply two *n* × *n* matrices over that field (Θ(*n*3) in big O notation).
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Better asymptotic bounds on the time required to multiply matrices have been known since the Strassen's algorithm in the 1960s, but the optimal time (that is, the computational complexity of matrix multiplication) remains unknown.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] As of September 2025, the best bound on the asymptotic complexity of a matrix multiplication algorithm is O(*n*2.371339) time, given by Alman, Duan, Williams, Xu, Xu, and Zhou.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] However, this algorithm is a galactic algorithm because of the large constants and cannot be realized practically.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] This algorithm takes time Θ(*nmp*) (in asymptotic notation).
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] A common simplification for the purpose of algorithm analysis is to assume that the inputs are all square matrices of size *n* × *n*, in which case the running time is Θ(*n*3), i.e., cubic in the size of the dimension.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The three loops in iterative matrix multiplication can be arbitrarily swapped with each other without an effect on correctness or asymptotic running time.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] However, the order can have a considerable impact on practical performance due to the memory access patterns and cache use of the algorithm; which order is best also depends on whether the matrices are stored in row-major order, column-major order, or a mix of both.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] In particular, in the idealized case of a fully associative cache consisting of M bytes and b bytes per cache line (i.e. ⁠*M*/*b*⁠ cache lines), the above algorithm is sub-optimal for A and B stored in row-major order.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] When *n* > ⁠*M*/*b*⁠, every iteration of the inner loop (a simultaneous sweep through a row of A and a column of B) incurs a cache miss when accessing an element of B.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] This means that the algorithm incurs Θ(*n*3) cache misses in the worst case.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] As of 2010, the speed of memories compared to that of processors is such that the cache misses, rather than the actual calculations, dominate the running time for sizable matrices.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] In the idealized cache model, this algorithm incurs only Θ(⁠*n*3/*b* √*M*⁠) cache misses; the divisor *b* √*M* amounts to several orders of magnitude on modern machines, so that the actual calculations dominate the running time, rather than the cache misses.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] An alternative to the iterative algorithm is the divide-and-conquer algorithm for matrix multiplication.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] which works for all square matrices whose dimensions are powers of two, i.e., the shapes are 2*n* × 2*n* for some n.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] which consists of eight multiplications of pairs of submatrices, followed by an addition step.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer algorithm computes the smaller multiplications recursively, using the scalar multiplication *c*11 = *a*11*b*11 as its base case.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] accounting for the eight recursive calls on matrices of size *n*/2 and Θ(*n*2) to sum the four pairs of resulting matrices element-wise.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Application of the master theorem for divide-and-conquer recurrences shows this recursion to have the solution Θ(*n*3), the same as the iterative algorithm.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] A variant of this algorithm that works for matrices of arbitrary shapes and is faster in practice splits matrices in two instead of four submatrices, as follows.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Splitting a matrix now means dividing it into two parts of equal size, or as close to equal sizes as possible in the case of odd dimensions.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Algorithms exist that provide better running times than the straightforward ones.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The first to be discovered was Strassen's algorithm, devised by Volker Strassen in 1969 and often referred to as "fast matrix multiplication".
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] It is based on a way of multiplying two 2×2 matrices which requires only 7 multiplications (instead of the usual 8), at the expense of several additional addition and subtraction operations.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Applying this recursively gives an algorithm with a multiplicative cost of $O(n^{\log _{2}7})\approx O(n^{2.807})$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Strassen's algorithm is more complex, and the numerical stability is reduced compared to the naïve algorithm, but it is faster in cases where *n* > 100 or so and appears in several libraries, such as BLAS.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] It is very useful for large matrices over exact domains such as finite fields, where numerical stability is not an issue.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Since Strassen's algorithm is actually used in practical numerical software and computer algebra systems, improving on the constants hidden in the big-O notation has its merits.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] A table that compares key aspects of the improved version based on recursive multiplication of 2×2-block matrices via 7 block matrix multiplications follows.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] As usual, n gives the dimensions of the matrix and M designates the memory size.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] It is known that a Strassen-like algorithm with a 2×2-block matrix step requires at least 7 block matrix multiplications.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] In 1976 Probert showed that such an algorithm requires at least 15 additions (including subtractions); however, a hidden assumption was that the blocks and the 2×2-block matrix are represented in the same basis.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Karstadt and Schwartz computed in different bases and traded 3 additions for less expensive basis transformations.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] They also proved that one cannot go below 12 additions per step using different bases.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] In subsequent work Beniamini et el. applied this base-change trick to more general decompositions than 2×2-block matrices and improved the leading constant for their run times.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] It is an open question in theoretical computer science how well Strassen's algorithm can be improved in terms of asymptotic complexity.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The *matrix multiplication exponent*, usually denoted $\omega$ , is the smallest real number for which any $n\times n$ matrix over a field can be multiplied together using $n^{\omega +o(1)}$ field operations.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The current best bound on $\omega$ is $\omega <2.371339$ , by Alman, Duan, Williams, Xu, Xu, and Zhou.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] This algorithm, like all other recent algorithms in this line of research, is a generalization of the Coppersmith–Winograd algorithm, which was given by Don Coppersmith and Shmuel Winograd in 1990.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The conceptual idea of these algorithms is similar to Strassen's algorithm: a way is devised for multiplying two *k* × *k*-matrices with fewer than *k*3 multiplications, and this technique is applied recursively.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] However, the constant coefficient hidden by the big-O notation is so large that these algorithms are only worthwhile for matrices that are too large to handle on present-day computers.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Victor Pan proposed so-called feasible sub-cubic matrix multiplication algorithms with an exponent slightly above 2.77, but in return with a much smaller hidden constant coefficient.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Freivalds' algorithm is a simple Monte Carlo algorithm that, given matrices A, B and C, verifies in Θ(*n*2) time if *AB* = *C*.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] In 2022, DeepMind introduced AlphaTensor, a neural network that used a single-player game analogy to invent thousands of matrix multiplication algorithms, including some previously discovered by humans and some that were not.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Operations were restricted to the non-commutative ground field (normal arithmetic) and finite field $\mathbb {Z} /2\mathbb {Z}$ (mod 2 arithmetic).
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The best "practical" (explicit low-rank decomposition of a matrix multiplication tensor) algorithm found ran in O(n2.778).
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Finding low-rank decompositions of such tensors (and beyond) is NP-hard; optimal multiplication even for 3×3 matrices remains unknown, even in commutative field.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] On 4×4 matrices, AlphaTensor unexpectedly discovered a solution with 47 multiplication steps, an improvement over the 49 required with Strassen’s algorithm of 1969, albeit restricted to mod 2 arithmetic.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Similarly, AlphaTensor solved 5×5 matrices with 96 rather than Strassen's 98 steps.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Based on the surprising discovery that such improvements exist, other researchers were quickly able to find a similar independent 4×4 algorithm, and separately tweaked Deepmind's 96-step 5×5 algorithm down to 95 steps in mod 2 arithmetic and to 97 in normal arithmetic.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Some algorithms were completely new: for example, (4, 5, 5) was improved to 76 steps from a baseline of 80 in both normal and mod 2 arithmetic.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer algorithm sketched earlier can be parallelized in two ways for shared-memory multiprocessors.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] can be performed independently of each other, as can the four summations (although the algorithm needs to "join" the multiplications before doing the summations).
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Here, *fork* is a keyword that signal a computation may be run in parallel with the rest of the function call, while *join* waits for all previously "forked" computations to complete. partition achieves its goal by pointer manipulation only.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] This algorithm has a critical path length of Θ(log2 *n*) steps, meaning it takes that much time on an ideal machine with an infinite number of processors; therefore, it has a maximum possible speedup of Θ(*n*3/log2 *n*) on any real computer.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The algorithm isn't practical due to the communication cost inherent in moving data to and from the temporary matrix T, but a more practical variant achieves Θ(*n*2) speedup, without using a temporary matrix.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] On modern architectures with hierarchical memory, the cost of loading and storing input matrix elements tends to dominate the cost of arithmetic.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] On a single machine this is the amount of data transferred between RAM and cache, while on a distributed memory multi-node machine it is the amount transferred between nodes; in either case it is called the *communication bandwidth*.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The naïve algorithm using three nested loops uses Ω(*n*3) communication bandwidth.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] Cannon's algorithm, also known as the *2D algorithm*, is a communication-avoiding algorithm that partitions each input matrix into a block matrix whose elements are submatrices of size √*M*/3 by √*M*/3, where *M* is the size of fast memory.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The naïve algorithm is then used over the block matrices, computing products of submatrices entirely in fast memory.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] This reduces communication bandwidth to *O*(*n*3/√*M*), which is asymptotically optimal (for algorithms performing Ω(*n*3) computation).
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] This can be improved by the *3D algorithm,* which arranges the processors in a 3D cube mesh, assigning every product of two input submatrices to a single processor.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The result submatrices are then generated by performing a reduction over each row.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] This algorithm transmits *O*(*n*2/*p*2/3) words per processor, which is asymptotically optimal.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] However, this requires replicating each input matrix element *p*1/3 times, and so requires a factor of *p*1/3 more memory than is needed to store the inputs.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] This algorithm can be combined with Strassen to further reduce runtime.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] "2.5D" algorithms provide a continuous tradeoff between memory usage and communication bandwidth.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] On modern distributed computing environments such as MapReduce, specialized multiplication algorithms have been developed.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] There are a variety of algorithms for multiplication on meshes.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] For multiplication of two *n*×*n* on a standard two-dimensional mesh using the 2D Cannon's algorithm, one can complete the multiplication in 3*n*-2 steps although this is reduced to half this number for repeated computations.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The standard array is inefficient because the data from the two matrices does not arrive simultaneously and it must be padded with zeroes.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The result is even faster on a two-layered cross-wired mesh, where only 2*n*-1 steps are needed.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The performance improves further for repeated computations leading to 100% efficiency.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] The cross-wired mesh array may be seen as a special case of a non-planar (i.e. multilayered) processing structure.
[src:strassen-matrix/coppersmith-winograd-algorithm] In a 3D mesh with *n*3 processing elements, two matrices can be multiplied in ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ using the DNS algorithm.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In computer science, **divide and conquer** is an algorithm design paradigm.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A divide-and-conquer algorithm recursively breaks down a problem into two or more sub-problems of the same or related type, until these become simple enough to be solved directly.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The solutions to the sub-problems are then combined to give a solution to the original problem.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Designing efficient divide-and-conquer algorithms can be difficult.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] As in mathematical induction, it is often necessary to generalize the problem to make it amenable to a recursive solution.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The correctness of a divide-and-conquer algorithm is usually proved by mathematical induction, and its computational cost is often determined by solving recurrence relations.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer paradigm is often used to find an optimal solution of a problem.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Its basic idea is to decompose a given problem into two or more similar, but simpler, subproblems, to solve them in turn, and to compose their solutions to solve the given problem.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Problems of sufficient simplicity are solved directly.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, to sort a given list of *n* natural numbers, split it into two lists of about *n*/2 numbers each, sort each of them in turn, and interleave both results appropriately to obtain the sorted version of the given list (see the picture).
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach is known as the merge sort algorithm.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The name "divide and conquer" is sometimes applied to algorithms that reduce each problem to only one sub-problem, such as the binary search algorithm for finding a record in a sorted list (or its analogue in numerical computing, the bisection algorithm for root finding).
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] These algorithms can be implemented more efficiently than general divide-and-conquer algorithms; in particular, if they use tail recursion, they can be converted into simple loops.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Under this broad definition, however, every algorithm that uses recursion or loops could be regarded as a "divide-and-conquer algorithm".
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Therefore, some authors consider that the name "divide and conquer" should be used only when each problem may generate two or more subproblems.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The name **decrease and conquer** has been proposed instead for the single-subproblem class.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Early examples of these algorithms are primarily decrease and conquer – the original problem is successively broken down into *single* subproblems, and indeed can be solved iteratively.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Binary search, a decrease-and-conquer algorithm where the subproblems are of roughly half the original size, has a long history.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] While a clear description of the algorithm on computers appeared in 1946 in an article by John Mauchly, the idea of using a sorted list of items to facilitate searching dates back at least as far as Babylonia in 200 BC.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Another ancient decrease-and-conquer algorithm is the Euclidean algorithm to compute the greatest common divisor of two numbers by reducing the numbers to smaller and smaller equivalent subproblems, which dates to several centuries BC.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] An early two-subproblem D&C algorithm that was specifically developed for computers and properly analyzed is the merge sort algorithm, invented by John von Neumann in 1945.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Another notable example is the algorithm invented by Anatolii A.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Karatsuba in 1960 that could multiply two *n*-digit numbers in $O(n^{\log _{2}3})$ operations (in Big O notation).
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This algorithm disproved Andrey Kolmogorov's 1956 conjecture that $\Omega (n^{2})$ operations would be required for that task.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This is related to a radix sort, described for punch-card sorting machines as early as 1929.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide and conquer is a powerful tool for solving conceptually difficult problems: all it requires is a way of breaking the problem into sub-problems, of solving the trivial cases, and of combining sub-problems to the original problem.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Similarly, decrease and conquer only requires reducing the problem to a single smaller problem, such as the classic Tower of Hanoi puzzle, which reduces moving a tower of height n to move a tower of height $n-1$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer paradigm often helps in the discovery of efficient algorithms.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] It was the key, for example, to Karatsuba's fast multiplication method, the quicksort and mergesort algorithms, the Strassen algorithm for matrix multiplication, and fast Fourier transforms.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In all these examples, the D&C approach led to an improvement in the asymptotic cost of the solution.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For other types of divide-and-conquer approaches, running times can also be generalized.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] If, instead, the work of splitting the problem and combining the partial solutions take $cn^{2}$ time, and there are 2 subproblems where each has size ${\frac {n}{2}}$ , then the running time of the divide-and-conquer algorithm is bounded by $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms are naturally adapted for execution in multi-processor machines, especially shared-memory systems where the communication of data between processors does not need to be planned in advance because distinct sub-problems can be executed on different processors.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms naturally tend to make efficient use of memory caches.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The reason is that once a sub-problem is small enough, it and all its sub-problems can, in principle, be solved within the cache, without accessing the slower main memory.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] An algorithm designed to exploit the cache in this way is called *cache-oblivious*, because it does not contain the cache size as an explicit parameter.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Moreover, D&C algorithms can be designed for important algorithms (e.g., sorting, FFTs, and matrix multiplication) to be *optimal* cache-oblivious algorithms–they use the cache in a probably optimal way, in an asymptotic sense, regardless of the cache size.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The same advantage exists with regards to other hierarchical storage systems, such as NUMA or virtual memory, as well as for multiple levels of cache: once a sub-problem is small enough, it can be solved within a given level of the hierarchy, without accessing the higher (slower) levels.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In computations with rounded arithmetic, e.g. with floating-point numbers, a divide-and-conquer algorithm may yield more accurate results than a superficially equivalent iterative method.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, one can add *N* numbers either by a simple loop that adds each datum to a single variable, or by a D&C algorithm called pairwise summation that breaks the data set into two halves, recursively computes the sum of each half, and then adds the two sums.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] While the second method performs the same number of additions as the first and pays the overhead of the recursive calls, it is usually more accurate.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms are naturally implemented as recursive procedures.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In that case, the partial sub-problems leading to the one currently being solved are automatically stored in the procedure call stack.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A recursive function is a function that calls itself within its definition.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms can also be implemented by a non-recursive program that stores the partial sub-problems in some explicit data structure, such as a stack, queue, or priority queue.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach allows more freedom in the choice of the sub-problem that is to be solved next, a feature that is important in some applications — e.g. in breadth-first recursion and the branch-and-bound method for function optimization.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach is also the standard solution in programming languages that do not provide support for recursive procedures.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In recursive implementations of D&C algorithms, one must make sure that there is sufficient memory allocated for the recursion stack, otherwise, the execution may fail because of stack overflow.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] D&C algorithms that are time-efficient often have relatively small recursion depth.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, the quicksort algorithm can be implemented so that it never requires more than $\log _{2}n$ nested recursive calls to sort n items.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Stack overflow can be difficult to prevent when using recursive procedures, since many compilers treat the recursion stack as a contiguous block of memory, and some reserve a fixed amount of space for it.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In addition, compilers may store more information on the recursion stack than is strictly required, including the return address, unchanged parameters, and the procedure’s local variables.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] As a result, the likelihood of stack overflow may be reduced by limiting the number of parameters and local variables in the recursive procedure, or by replacing recursion with an explicit stack data structure.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In any recursive algorithm, there is considerable freedom in the choice of the *base cases*, the small subproblems that are solved directly in order to terminate the recursion.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Choosing the smallest or simplest possible base cases is more elegant and usually leads to simpler programs, because there are fewer cases to consider and they are easier to solve.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, a Fast Fourier Transform algorithm could stop the recursion when the input is a single sample, and the quicksort list-sorting algorithm could stop when the input is the empty list; in both examples, there is only one base case to consider, and it requires no processing.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] On the other hand, efficiency often improves if the recursion is stopped at relatively large base cases, and these are solved non-recursively, resulting in a hybrid algorithm.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This strategy avoids the overhead of recursive calls that do little or no work and may also allow the use of specialized non-recursive algorithms that, for those base cases, are more efficient than explicit recursion.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A general procedure for a simple hybrid recursive algorithm is *short-circuiting the base case*, also known as *arm's-length recursion*.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In this case, whether the next step will result in the base case is checked before the function call, avoiding an unnecessary function call.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, in a tree, rather than recursing to a child node and then checking whether it is null, checking null before recursing avoids half the function calls in some algorithms on binary trees.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Since a D&C algorithm eventually reduces each problem or sub-problem instance to a large number of base instances, these often dominate the overall cost of the algorithm, especially when the splitting/joining overhead is low.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Note that these considerations do not depend on whether recursion is implemented by the compiler or by an explicit stack.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Thus, for example, many library implementations of quicksort will switch to a simple loop-based insertion sort (or similar) algorithm once the number of items to be sorted is sufficiently small.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Note that, if the empty list were the only base case, sorting a list with n entries would entail maximally n quicksort calls that would do nothing but return immediately.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Increasing the base cases to lists of size 2 or less will eliminate most of those do-nothing calls, and more generally a base case larger than 2 is typically used to reduce the fraction of time spent in function-call overhead or stack manipulation.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, this approach is used in some efficient FFT implementations, where the base cases are unrolled implementations of divide-and-conquer FFT algorithms for a set of fixed sizes.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Source-code generation methods may be used to produce the large number of separate base cases desirable to implement this strategy efficiently.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The generalized version of this idea is known as recursion "unrolling" or "coarsening", and various techniques have been proposed for automating the procedure of enlarging the base case.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For some problems, the branched recursion may end up evaluating the same sub-problem many times over.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In such cases it may be worth identifying and saving the solutions to these overlapping subproblems, a technique which is commonly known as memoization.
[src:strassen-matrix/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Followed to the limit, it leads to bottom-up divide-and-conquer algorithms such as dynamic programming.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] In linear algebra, the **Strassen algorithm**, named after Volker Strassen, is an algorithm for matrix multiplication.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] It is faster than the standard matrix multiplication algorithm for large matrices, with a better asymptotic complexity ( $O(n^{\log _{2}7})$ versus $O(n^{3})$ ), although the naive algorithm is often better for smaller matrices.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] The Strassen algorithm is slower than the fastest known algorithms for extremely large matrices, but such galactic algorithms are not useful in practice, as they are much slower for matrices of practical size.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] For small matrices even faster algorithms exist.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] Strassen's algorithm works for any ring, such as plus/multiply, but not all semirings, such as min-plus or boolean algebra, where the naive algorithm still works, and so called combinatorial matrix multiplication.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] Volker Strassen first published this algorithm in 1969 and thereby proved that the $n^{3}$ general matrix multiplication algorithm was not optimal.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] The Strassen algorithm's publication resulted in more research about matrix multiplication that led to both asymptotically lower bounds and improved computational upper bounds.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] Let A , B be two square matrices over a ring ${\mathcal {R}}$ , for example matrices whose entries are integers or the real numbers.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] The goal of matrix multiplication is to calculate the matrix product $C=AB$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] This construction does not reduce the number of multiplications: 8 multiplications of matrix blocks are still needed to calculate the $C_{ij}$ matrices, the same number of multiplications needed when using standard matrix multiplication.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] using only 7 multiplications (one for each $M_{k}$ ) instead of 8.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] We recursively iterate this division process until the submatrices degenerate into numbers (elements of the ring ${\mathcal {R}}$ ).
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] If, as mentioned above, the original matrix had a size that was not a power of 2, then the resulting product will have zero rows and columns just like A and B , and these will then be stripped at this point to obtain the (smaller) matrix C we really wanted.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] Practical implementations of Strassen's algorithm switch to standard methods of matrix multiplication for small enough submatrices, for which those algorithms are more efficient.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] The particular crossover point for which Strassen's algorithm is more efficient depends on the specific implementation and hardware.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] Earlier authors had estimated that Strassen's algorithm is faster for matrices with widths from 32 to 128 for optimized implementations.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] A more recent study (2016) observed benefits for matrices as small as 512 and a benefit around 20%.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] This reduces the number of matrix additions and subtractions from 18 to 15.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] The number of matrix multiplications is still 7, and the asymptotic complexity is the same.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] The outline of the algorithm above showed that one can get away with just 7, instead of the traditional 8, matrix-matrix multiplications for the sub-blocks of the matrix.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] The question then is how many operations exactly one needs for Strassen's algorithms, and how this compares with the standard matrix multiplication that takes approximately $2N^{3}$ (where $N=2^{n}$ ) arithmetic operations, i.e. an asymptotic complexity $\Theta (N^{3})$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] The number of additions and multiplications required in the Strassen algorithm can be calculated as follows: let $f(n)$ be the number of operations for a $2^{n}\times 2^{n}$ matrix.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] Then by recursive application of the Strassen algorithm, we see that $f(n)=7f(n-1)+l4^{n}$ , for some constant l that depends on the number of additions performed at each application of the algorithm.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] The reduction in the number of arithmetic operations however comes at the price of a somewhat reduced numerical stability, and the algorithm also requires significantly more memory compared to the naive algorithm.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] Both initial matrices must have their dimensions expanded to the next power of 2, which results in storing up to four times as many elements, and the seven auxiliary matrices each contain a quarter of the elements in the expanded ones.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] Strassen's algorithm needs to be compared to the "naive" way of doing the matrix multiplication that would require 8 instead of 7 multiplications of sub-blocks.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] This would then give rise to the complexity one expects from the standard approach: $O(8^{n})=O(N^{\log _{2}8})=O(N^{3})$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] The comparison of these two algorithms shows that *asymptotically*, Strassen's algorithm is faster: There exists a size $N_{\text{threshold}}$ so that matrices that are larger are more efficiently multiplied with Strassen's algorithm than the "traditional" way.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] However, the asymptotic statement does not imply that Strassen's algorithm is *always* faster even for small matrices, and in practice this is in fact not the case: For small matrices, the cost of the additional additions of matrix blocks outweighs the savings in the number of multiplications.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] There are also other factors not captured by the analysis above, such as the difference in cost on today's hardware between loading data from memory onto processors vs. the cost of actually doing operations on this data.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] As a consequence of these sorts of considerations, Strassen's algorithm is typically only used on "large" matrices.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] This kind of effect is even more pronounced with alternative algorithms such as the one by Coppersmith and Winograd: While *asymptotically* even faster, the cross-over point $N_{\text{threshold}}$ is so large that the algorithm is not generally used on matrices one encounters in practice.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] The bilinear complexity or **rank** of a bilinear map is an important concept in the asymptotic complexity of matrix multiplication.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] In other words, the rank of a bilinear map is the length of its shortest bilinear computation.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] The existence of Strassen's algorithm shows that the rank of $2\times 2$ matrix multiplication is no more than seven.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] To see this, let us express this algorithm (alongside the standard algorithm) as such a bilinear computation.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] It can be shown that the total number of elementary multiplications L required for matrix multiplication is tightly asymptotically bound to the rank R , i.e. $L=\Theta (R)$ , or more specifically, since the constants are known, $R/2\leq L\leq R$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] One useful property of the rank is that it is submultiplicative for tensor products, and this enables one to show that $2^{n}\times 2^{n}\times 2^{n}$ matrix multiplication can be accomplished with no more than $7^{n}$ elementary multiplications for any n .
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] Strassen's algorithm is cache oblivious.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] cache misses during its execution, assuming an idealized cache of size M (i.e. with $M/b$ lines of length b ).
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] The description above states that the matrices are square, and the size is a power of two, and that padding should be used if needed.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] This restriction allows the matrices to be split in half, recursively, until limit of scalar multiplication is reached.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] The restriction simplifies the explanation, and analysis of complexity, but is not actually necessary; and in fact, padding the matrix as described will increase the computation time and can easily eliminate the fairly narrow time savings obtained by using the method in the first place.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] Furthermore, there is no need for the matrices to be square.
[src:strassen-matrix/strassen-algorithm] Non-square matrices can be split in half using the same methods, yielding smaller non-square matrices.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] In theoretical computer science, the **time complexity** is the computational complexity that describes the amount of computer time it takes to run an algorithm.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Time complexity is commonly estimated by counting the number of elementary operations performed by the algorithm, supposing that each elementary operation takes a fixed amount of time to perform.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Thus, the amount of time taken and the number of elementary operations performed by the algorithm are taken to be related by a constant factor.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Since an algorithm's running time may vary among different inputs of the same size, one commonly considers the worst-case time complexity, which is the maximum amount of time required for inputs of a given size.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Less common, and usually specified explicitly, is the average-case complexity, which is the average of the time taken on inputs of a given size (this makes sense because there are only a finite number of possible inputs of a given size).
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] In both cases, the time complexity is generally expressed as a function of the size of the input.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Since this function is generally difficult to compute exactly, and the running time for small inputs is usually not consequential, one commonly focuses on the behavior of the complexity when the input size increases—that is, the asymptotic behavior of the complexity.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Therefore, the time complexity is commonly expressed using big O notation, typically $O(n)$ , $O(n\log n)$ , $O(n^{\alpha })$ , $O(2^{n})$ , etc., where n is the size in units of bits needed to represent the input.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Algorithmic complexities are classified according to the type of function appearing in the big O notation.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] For example, an algorithm with time complexity $O(n)$ is a *linear time algorithm* and an algorithm with time complexity $O(n^{\alpha })$ for some constant $\alpha >0$ is a *polynomial time algorithm*.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] The following table summarizes some classes of commonly encountered time complexities.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An algorithm is termed **constant time** (often represented as ${\textstyle O(1)}$ time) when its complexity function ${\textstyle T(n)}$ is bounded by a value that does not change with the size of the input.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] This implies that the execution time remains consistent regardless of how much data is processed.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] For instance, accessing a specific element in an array is a constant-time operation, as it requires only a single operation to locate that element.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] In contrast, determining the minimum value in an unordered array is not constant time; it requires examining each element, resulting in linear time complexity, or ${\textstyle O(n)}$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] However, if the number of elements is known and fixed, certain tasks can still be considered constant time.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Importantly, the term "constant time" does not mean the running time must be entirely independent of the problem size; rather, it should have a consistent upper bound irrespective of input size.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] For example, a task that involves swapping the values of a and b to ensure ${\textstyle a\leq b}$ is classified as constant time, even if the execution time may vary depending on whether the condition is already met.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] The key is that there exists a constant t such that the time taken will never exceed t, regardless of the input values.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Constant-time algorithms are especially significant in contexts like cryptography, where timing attacks can exploit variations in execution time.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] By designing algorithms that run in constant time, developers can enhance security and ensure performance predictability, making it a fundamental consideration in software engineering.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to take **logarithmic time** when $T(n)=O(\log n)$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Since $\log _{a}n$ and $\log _{b}n$ are related by a constant multiplier, and such a multiplier is irrelevant to big O classification, the standard usage for logarithmic-time algorithms is $O(\log n)$ regardless of the base of the logarithm appearing in the expression of T.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Algorithms taking logarithmic time are commonly found in operations on binary trees or when using binary search.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An $O(\log n)$ algorithm is considered highly efficient, as the ratio of the number of operations to the size of the input decreases and tends to zero when n increases.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An algorithm that must access all elements of its input cannot take logarithmic time, as the time taken for reading an input of size n is of the order of n.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An example of logarithmic time is given by dictionary search.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Consider a dictionary *D* which contains n entries, sorted in alphabetical order.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] We suppose that, for $1\leq k\leq n$ , one may access the kth entry of the dictionary in a constant time.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Under these hypotheses, the test to see if a word w is in the dictionary may be done in logarithmic time: consider $D\left(\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor \right)$ , where $\lfloor \;\rfloor$ denotes the floor function.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] If $w=D\left(\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor \right)$ --that is to say, the word w is exactly in the middle of the dictionary--then we are done.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Otherwise, if it comes after the middle word, continue similarly with the right half of the dictionary.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] This algorithm is similar to the method often used to find an entry in a paper dictionary.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] As a result, the search space within the dictionary decreases as the algorithm gets closer to the target word.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **polylogarithmic time** if its time $T(n)$ is $O{\bigl (}(\log n)^{k}{\bigr )}$ for some constant k.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Another way to write this is $O(\log ^{k}n)$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] For example, matrix chain ordering can be solved in polylogarithmic time on a parallel random-access machine, and a graph can be determined to be planar in a fully dynamic way in $O(\log ^{3}n)$ time per insert/delete operation.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **sub-linear time** (often spelled **sublinear time**) if $T(n)=o(n)$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] In particular this includes algorithms with the time complexities defined above.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] The specific term *sublinear time algorithm* commonly refers to randomized algorithms that sample a small fraction of their inputs and process them efficiently to approximately infer properties of the entire instance.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] This type of sublinear time algorithm is closely related to property testing and statistics.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to take **linear time**, or $O(n)$ time, if its time complexity is $O(n)$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Informally, this means that the running time increases at most linearly with the size of the input.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] More precisely, this means that there is a constant c such that the running time is at most $cn$ for every input of size n.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] For example, a procedure that adds up all elements of a list requires time proportional to the length of the list, if the adding time is constant, or, at least, bounded by a constant.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Linear time is the best possible time complexity in situations where the algorithm has to sequentially read its entire input.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Therefore, much research has been invested into discovering algorithms exhibiting linear time or, at least, nearly linear time.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] This research includes both software and hardware methods.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] There are several hardware technologies which exploit parallelism to provide this.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An example is content-addressable memory.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] This concept of linear time is used in string matching algorithms such as the Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm and Ukkonen's algorithm.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **quasilinear time** (also referred to as **log-linear time**) if $T(n)=O(n\log ^{k}n)$ for some positive constant k; **linearithmic time** is the case $k=1$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Using soft O notation these algorithms are ${\tilde {O}}(n)$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Quasilinear time algorithms are also $O(n^{1+\varepsilon })$ for every constant $\varepsilon >0$ and thus run faster than any polynomial time algorithm whose time bound includes a term $n^{c}$ for any $c>1$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] In many cases, the $O(n\log n)$ running time is simply the result of performing a $\Theta (\log n)$ operation n times (for the notation, see Big O notation § Family of Bachmann–Landau notations).
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] For example, binary tree sort creates a binary tree by inserting each element of the n-sized array one by one.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Since the insert operation on a self-balancing binary search tree takes $O(\log n)$ time, the entire algorithm takes $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Comparison sorts require at least $\Omega (n\log n)$ comparisons in the worst case because $\log(n!)=\Theta (n\log n)$ , by Stirling's approximation.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] They also frequently arise from the recurrence relation ${\textstyle T(n)=2T\left({\frac {n}{2}}\right)+O(n)}$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **subquadratic time** if $T(n)=o(n^{2})$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] For example, simple, comparison-based sorting algorithms are quadratic (e.g. insertion sort), but more advanced algorithms can be found that are subquadratic (e.g. shell sort).
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] No general-purpose sorts run in linear time, but the change from quadratic to sub-quadratic is of great practical importance.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be of **polynomial time** if its running time is upper bounded by a polynomial expression in the size of the input for the algorithm, that is, *T*(*n*) = *O*(*n**k*) for some positive constant *k*.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Problems for which a deterministic polynomial-time algorithm exists belong to the complexity class **P**, which is central in the field of computational complexity theory.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Cobham's thesis states that polynomial time is a synonym for "tractable", "feasible", "efficient", or "fast".
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] These two concepts are only relevant if the inputs to the algorithms consist of integers.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] The concept of polynomial time leads to several complexity classes in computational complexity theory.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Some important classes defined using polynomial time are the following.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] P is the smallest time-complexity class on a deterministic machine which is robust in terms of machine model changes.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An algorithm is defined to take **superpolynomial time** if *T*(*n*) is not bounded above by any polynomial; that is, if ⁠ $T(n)\not \in O(n^{c})$ ⁠ for every positive integer *c*.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] For example, an algorithm that runs for 2*n* steps on an input of size *n* requires superpolynomial time (more specifically, exponential time).
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An algorithm that uses exponential resources is clearly superpolynomial, but some algorithms are only very weakly superpolynomial.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] For example, the Adleman–Pomerance–Rumely primality test runs for *n**O*(log log *n*) time on *n*-bit inputs; this grows faster than any polynomial for large enough *n*, but the input size must become impractically large before it cannot be dominated by a polynomial with small degree.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An algorithm that requires superpolynomial time lies outside the complexity class **P**.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Cobham's thesis posits that these algorithms are impractical, and in many cases they are.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Since the P versus NP problem is unresolved, it is unknown whether NP-complete problems require superpolynomial time.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] There are some problems for which we know quasi-polynomial time algorithms, but no polynomial time algorithm is known.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Other computational problems with quasi-polynomial time solutions but no known polynomial time solution include the planted clique problem in which the goal is to find a large clique in the union of a clique and a random graph.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] The complexity class **QP** consists of all problems that have quasi-polynomial time algorithms.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] It can be defined in terms of DTIME as follows.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] In complexity theory, the unsolved P versus NP problem asks if all problems in NP have polynomial-time algorithms.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] All the best-known algorithms for NP-complete problems like 3SAT etc. take exponential time.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Indeed, it is conjectured for many natural NP-complete problems that they do not have sub-exponential time algorithms.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Here "sub-exponential time" is taken to mean the second definition presented below.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] (On the other hand, many graph problems represented in the natural way by adjacency matrices are solvable in subexponential time simply because the size of the input is the square of the number of vertices.) This conjecture (for the k-SAT problem) is known as the exponential time hypothesis.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Since it is conjectured that NP-complete problems do not have quasi-polynomial time algorithms, some inapproximability results in the field of approximation algorithms make the assumption that NP-complete problems do not have quasi-polynomial time algorithms.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] For example, see the known inapproximability results for the set cover problem.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] The term **sub-exponential time** is used to express that the running time of some algorithm may grow faster than any polynomial but is still significantly smaller than an exponential.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] In this sense, problems that have sub-exponential time algorithms are somewhat more tractable than those that only have exponential algorithms.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] The precise definition of "sub-exponential" is not generally agreed upon, however the two most widely used are below.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] A problem is said to be sub-exponential time solvable if it can be solved in running times whose logarithms grow smaller than any given polynomial.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] More precisely, a problem is in sub-exponential time if for every *ε* > 0 there exists an algorithm which solves the problem in time *O*(2*n**ε*).
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] The set of all such problems is the complexity class **SUBEXP** which can be defined in terms of DTIME as follows.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] This notion of sub-exponential is non-uniform in terms of *ε* in the sense that *ε* is not part of the input and each ε may have its own algorithm for the problem.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Some authors define sub-exponential time as running times in $2^{o(n)}$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] This definition allows larger running times than the first definition of sub-exponential time.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An example of such a sub-exponential time algorithm is the best-known classical algorithm for integer factorization, the general number field sieve, which runs in time about $2^{{O}(n^{1/3}(\log n)^{2/3})}$ , where the length of the input is n.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Another example was the graph isomorphism problem, which the best known algorithm from 1982 to 2016 solved in $2^{O\left({\sqrt {n\log n}}\right)}$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] However, at STOC 2016 a quasi-polynomial time algorithm was presented.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] It makes a difference whether the algorithm is allowed to be sub-exponential in the size of the instance, the number of vertices, or the number of edges.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] In parameterized complexity, this difference is made explicit by considering pairs $(L,k)$ of decision problems and parameters *k*.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] More precisely, SUBEPT is the class of all parameterized problems $(L,k)$ for which there is a computable function $f:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ with $f\in o(k)$ and an algorithm that decides *L* in time $2^{f(k)}\cdot {\textsf {poly}}(n)$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] The **exponential time hypothesis** (**ETH**) is that 3SAT, the satisfiability problem of Boolean formulas in conjunctive normal form with at most three literals per clause and with *n* variables, cannot be solved in time 2*o*(*n*).
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] More precisely, the hypothesis is that there is some absolute constant *c* > 0 such that 3SAT cannot be decided in time 2*cn* by any deterministic Turing machine.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] With *m* denoting the number of clauses, ETH is equivalent to the hypothesis that *k*SAT cannot be solved in time 2*o*(*m*) for any integer *k* ≥ 3.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] The exponential time hypothesis implies P ≠ NP.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **exponential time**, if *T*(*n*) is upper bounded by 2poly(*n*), where poly(*n*) is some polynomial in *n*.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] More formally, an algorithm is exponential time if *T*(*n*) is bounded by *O*(2*n**k*) for some constant *k*.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Problems which admit exponential time algorithms on a deterministic Turing machine form the complexity class known as **EXP**.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Sometimes, exponential time is used to refer to algorithms that have *T*(*n*) = 2*O*(*n*), where the exponent is at most a linear function of *n*.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] This gives rise to the complexity class **E**.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **factorial time** if *T(n)* is upper bounded by the factorial function *n!*.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Factorial time is a subset of exponential time (EXP) because $n!\leq n^{n}=2^{n\log n}=O\left(2^{n^{1+\epsilon }}\right)$ for all $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An example of an algorithm that runs in factorial time is bogosort, a notoriously inefficient sorting algorithm based on trial and error.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Bogosort sorts a list of *n* items by repeatedly shuffling the list until it is found to be sorted.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] In the average case, each pass through the bogosort algorithm will examine one of the *n*! orderings of the *n* items.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] If the items are distinct, only one such ordering is sorted.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Bogosort shares patrimony with the infinite monkey theorem.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be double exponential time if *T*(*n*) is upper bounded by 22poly(*n*), where poly(*n*) is some polynomial in *n*.
[src:strassen-matrix/time-complexity] Such algorithms belong to the complexity class 2-EXPTIME.
